SALES_KNOWLEDGE_BASE = """
COMMERCIAL VEHICLE SALES INTELLIGENCE — INDUSTRY KNOWLEDGE

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
1. MARKET DYNAMICS & DEALER BEHAVIOR
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

DEALER TYPES & WHAT THEY SIGNAL:
- High-volume / multi-brand dealers (50+ units): Relationship-driven buyers. They've seen every pitch. Lead with data they don't have — market positioning, competitive gaps in their inventory mix. They buy on margin opportunity, not product features.
- Mid-size specialists (15-50 units): Often the best conversion targets. Big enough to matter, small enough that a new builder relationship moves the needle. Watch for body type concentration — a dealer running 70%+ in one segment is signaling demand they'd scale if supply improved.
- Small/regional dealers (<15 units): Evaluate carefully. Low inventory can mean low volume OR it can mean fast turns (selling before restocking). Check velocity: if they're churning units fast, they're punching above their weight.
- Dealers with declining inventory: Not always bad news. Could be tightening focus on profitable segments, clearing aged stock before a chassis brand switch, or seasonal drawdown. Look at WHAT left, not just how much.

BUYING CYCLE PATTERNS:
- Q1 (Jan-Mar): Budget season. Fleet managers allocate annual spend. Municipal/government buyers issue RFPs. Best time for new relationship pitches — budgets are fresh and buyers are planning.
- Q2 (Apr-Jun): Peak ordering. Construction season drives service truck/flatbed demand. Dealers stock up. Highest conversion window for body types tied to outdoor trades (service, utility, flatbed, dump).
- Q3 (Jul-Sep): Steady-state. Reorders on fast-moving segments. Good time for competitive displacement — dealers know what's selling and what's sitting. If a competitor's product is aging on the lot, that's your opening.
- Q4 (Oct-Dec): Use-it-or-lose-it budget spend. Government and large fleet buyers rush remaining capital. Also: model year transitions create urgency. Dealers want to clear current-year inventory.

FLEET VS RETAIL SIGNALS:
- Dealers pricing consistently above market (+10%+) are selling retail/end-user — they value brand reputation, warranty, and service support. Position on quality and total cost of ownership.
- Dealers pricing at or below market are likely fleet/wholesale accounts — they buy on volume pricing, delivery speed, and spec flexibility. Position on capacity and turnaround.
- Mixed pricing across body types = segmented strategy. They may retail service trucks (high margin) while wholesaling flatbeds (commodity). Tailor the pitch per segment.

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
2. READING INVENTORY SIGNALS
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

WHAT INVENTORY MIX TELLS YOU:
- Body type concentration >60% in one category: This dealer has a niche. They know their customer base. Don't pitch diversification — pitch being the best supplier in their dominant segment.
- Even distribution across 4+ body types: Generalist dealer. They serve varied demand. Pitch breadth of catalog and one-stop convenience.
- High chassis brand diversity (3+ brands): Flexible buyer, not brand-loyal. They'll switch builders if the value prop is right. Emphasize competitive advantages.
- Single chassis brand loyalty: Likely has an OEM relationship or dealer agreement. Harder to displace on chassis, but body builder choice is often independent. That's your angle.

GROWTH & DECLINE INDICATORS:
- Inventory up + new units appearing: Active growth. They're investing. Best time to pitch — they're already spending.
- Inventory up + units aging (no sold units): Stagnation. They're overstocked. Not ideal for "buy more" pitch, but ripe for "buy better" — help them move what's sitting by offering a more marketable build.
- Inventory down + high velocity: Healthy business, fast turns. These dealers need reliable supply above all else. Pitch consistency and delivery predictability.
- Inventory flat + builder mix shifting: They're switching suppliers. Critical signal. Find out who they're moving away from and why — that's the conversation opener.

COMPETITIVE SWITCHING CUES:
- Declining share of a specific builder in their mix = dissatisfaction or supply issues. Mention it: "I noticed your Reading inventory dropped 40% — supply issues or looking for alternatives?"
- New builder appearing that wasn't there last month = they're actively evaluating. Time-sensitive opportunity.
- Price premium on one builder's units vs another = the premium builder is their preferred product. The discount builder may be filler they'd replace.

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
3. PRICING STRATEGY INTELLIGENCE
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

READING PRICE POSITIONING:
- Premium dealers (>10% above market avg): Value quality, brand, and features. They have customers willing to pay more. Compete on build quality, warranty, customization. Never lead with price.
- Market-rate dealers (±10%): Pragmatic buyers. They want competitive pricing with solid quality. Lead with value proposition — what do they get that others don't at this price point.
- Value dealers (>10% below market avg): Volume-driven or fleet-focused. They compress margins to move units. Only compete here if you can match on price AND offer something extra (faster delivery, better warranty, spec flexibility).

PRICE ELASTICITY BY SEGMENT:
- Service trucks / utility bodies: Lower price sensitivity. End users (plumbers, electricians, contractors) buy on functionality and upfit options. Dealers can mark up significantly. High-margin segment.
- Flatbeds / platform bodies: Higher price sensitivity. More commoditized product. Dealers compete on price. Win here on delivery speed and chassis compatibility, not features.
- Box vans / dry freight: Mid-range sensitivity. Size and payload specs drive the buy. Competitive on spec-for-spec pricing.
- Dump bodies: Price-sensitive but quality-conscious. Construction buyers beat up equipment — they'll pay more for durability but shop aggressively. Warranty is a differentiator.
- Specialty (crane, mechanics, fuel/lube): Low price sensitivity, high spec sensitivity. These are engineered solutions. The buyer cares about capability, not sticker price. Longest sales cycle but highest margin.

MARGIN SIGNALS FROM DATA:
- Wide price spread within a body type at one dealer = custom builds or mixed spec levels. Dig into the inventory detail.
- Tight price clustering = standardized builds, fleet orders. They value consistency.
- Dealer pricing significantly different from state average = either premium positioning (good) or desperation pricing (investigate).

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
4. TERRITORY & ROUTE PLAYBOOK
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

VISIT PRIORITIZATION FRAMEWORK:
Tier 1 — Visit monthly: Hot leads (score 70+). High product fit, low penetration, growing inventory. These are your "money meetings."
Tier 2 — Visit quarterly: Warm leads (score 40-69). Moderate scores, decent fit, room to grow. Competitive displacement targets.
Tier 3 — Visit semi-annually: Cold leads (score <40). Small dealers, poor fit, or already well-penetrated. Check for inventory mix shifts that could upgrade them.
Tier 4 — Phone/email only: Low-volume dealers with poor product fit. Not worth windshield time unless they're geographically convenient (add to an existing route as a bonus stop).

GEOGRAPHIC CLUSTERING STRATEGY:
- Build routes around 2-3 Tier 1 dealers, then fill gaps with Tier 2/3 stops that are geographically convenient. Never drive 2 hours for a Tier 3 visit alone.
- Metro areas (Atlanta, Dallas, Charlotte, Nashville): Dense dealer clusters. Plan full days — 4-6 visits possible. Mix tiers to balance high-value meetings with relationship maintenance.
- Rural/suburban corridors: Longer drive times. Plan 2-3 targeted visits per day max. Every stop needs to justify the windshield time.
- State borders: Don't ignore cross-state opportunities. A dealer 20 min across the state line from your last stop is better than one 3 hours away in-territory.

DAY-PLANNING METHODOLOGY:
- Morning (8-10 AM): Lead with your best meeting. Decision-makers are fresh, available, and haven't been pitched yet that day.
- Mid-day (10 AM-2 PM): Volume visits. Quick check-ins, relationship touches, drop-offs.
- Afternoon (2-4 PM): Second-best meeting. Catch decision-makers before end-of-day.
- Avoid Friday afternoons for first visits — dealership energy is low. Use Fridays for admin, call prep, and route planning for next week.

COLD VS WARM APPROACH:
- Cold (no existing relationship): Research first. Know their inventory mix, top body types, pricing position, and competitive builder mix BEFORE walking in. Opening line should reference something specific about their business, not a generic pitch. "I see you're running 60 service trucks mostly with [builder] — how's their delivery been?"
- Warm (existing relationship): Lead with value-add. Bring market intel: "Your segment is up 15% in Georgia this quarter" or "I noticed [competitor dealer] nearby just added 30 units — want to see how your pricing compares?"
- Re-engagement (lapsed relationship): Acknowledge the gap. Bring something new — a data insight, a market shift, a product update. "We haven't connected since [timeframe] — a lot's changed in the market. Here's what I'm seeing in your area."

SEASONAL ROUTE ADJUSTMENTS:
- Spring (Mar-May): Hit construction-heavy territories. Service truck and flatbed demand spikes. Prioritize dealers with high body type match in those segments.
- Summer (Jun-Aug): Steady routes, focus on reorders and competitive displacement. Good time for new prospect visits — dealers are busy and receptive to supply options.
- Fall (Sep-Nov): Government/municipal push. Target dealers near military bases, county seats, and state capitals. Budget deadlines create urgency.
- Winter (Dec-Feb): Plan and prep. Update territory maps, review score changes, identify dealers whose mix shifted. Use this time to build Q1 target lists.

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
5. COMPETITIVE ANALYSIS FRAMEWORK
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

READING BUILDER MIX:
- A dealer carrying 3+ body builders is actively comparing. They're not locked in. Each builder is being tested against the others on quality, price, delivery, and dealer support.
- A dealer with 80%+ from one builder has a strong relationship or an exclusive deal. Displacement requires a compelling event — quality failure, supply disruption, or price increase from the incumbent.
- When a new builder appears in a dealer's mix for the first time, that dealer is in evaluation mode. This is the highest-urgency signal for competitive engagement.

DISPLACEMENT STRATEGY:
- Never trash-talk the incumbent. Instead: "I see you're running a lot of [builder]. How are they treating you on [specific pain point — delivery, warranty, customization]?"
- Target the incumbent's weakness. If market data shows their units sit longer (high age), mention turn rates. If their pricing is above market, mention value.
- Start with a small win. Don't ask them to switch everything — propose a trial order in one body type. Let the product prove itself. "Try 5 service bodies and compare turn rate and customer feedback to what you're running now."
- Supply chain disruptions are displacement gold. If a builder has delivery backlogs (visible in data as declining new unit counts industry-wide), position reliability.

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
6. PRE-CALL INTELLIGENCE FRAMEWORK
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

BEFORE EVERY CALL OR VISIT, KNOW:
1. Their inventory size and trajectory (growing, flat, declining?)
2. Their body type mix (what do they sell most? what's missing?)
3. Their builder mix (who are they buying from? any recent changes?)
4. Their pricing position (premium, market, or value?)
5. Their lead score and WHY (what makes them hot, warm, or cold?)
6. Their competitive landscape (who else is nearby? what do neighbors stock?)

CONVERSATION STARTERS FROM DATA:
- Inventory growth: "I see you've added 25 units since last quarter — business must be strong. What's driving the growth?"
- Body type gap: "You're running 45 service trucks but I don't see any [your category] — is that a segment your customers ask about?"
- Price positioning: "Your pricing is running about 12% above the Georgia average — you've clearly built a premium brand. How do you select your body builders?"
- Builder concentration: "You're almost exclusively [builder] on your service bodies. Have you evaluated alternatives recently?"
- Competitive proximity: "Did you know [nearby dealer] just added 30 flatbeds? That's a lot of new capacity in your market."
- Velocity signal: "You moved 18 units last month — that's top-10 velocity in the state. What's your biggest supply bottleneck?"

WHAT TO LISTEN FOR:
- "We can't get enough [body type]" = supply problem. Position delivery reliability.
- "Our customers keep asking for [feature]" = unmet demand. Position customization.
- "[Builder] raised prices again" = cost pressure. Position value without cheapening.
- "We're thinking about adding [body type]" = expansion mode. Position as the partner for new segments.
- "We've had quality issues with [builder]" = active pain. Move fast — they're already looking.
"""

